":"1338–1437","–Male":"Deceased","1375–1406":"1375–1406","1377–Male":"1377–Deceased","1437":"1437","1338":"1338","1377":"1377","1421":"1421","1375":"1375","ABT 1377":"about 1377","1350":"1350","1 October 1406":"1 October 1406","1406":"1406","Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Donegal and Westmeath) and English: variant of   Carey  .","French: variant of   Carry   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Decorah","meanings":["Americanized form of <b>de Carrie</b>, itself an altered form of French <b>Decary</b>, a variant of   Cary   2, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’. It is found mainly among the Ho-Chunk (i.e. Winnebago) Native American people in WI.","History: The progenitor of the Decorahs was a French soldier, Joseph Sabrevoir de Carrie, who in 1729 settled for a time among the Winnebagos on Doty Island, WI, and married an Indian woman, known in English as Glory of the Morning. Decorah, a city in IA, is named after one of their descendants, Waukon Decorah (<i>c.</i> 1780–1868), a chief of the Winnebago."]},{"name":"Carey","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardha</b>, a midland surname meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ciardha</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>ciar</i> ‘dark, black’. See   Kerry  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhiachra</b> ‘son of <i>Fiachra</i>’.","English: from Carey Barton in Devon or Castle Cary, Lytes Cary, Cary Fitzpaine, or Babcary, all in Somerset, named for the rivers on which they stand; both river names probably derive from the Celtic root <i>car-</i> ‘love, liking’, perhaps with the meaning ‘pleasant stream’."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma Cary Of Wiltshire was born in 1350, in Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Drewe in 1377, in Southampton, Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1421, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1350–1421":"1350–1421","1338–1437":"1338–1437","–Male":"Surnud","1375–1406":"1375–1406","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1437":"1437","1338":"1338","1377":"1377","1421":"1421","1375":"1375","ABT 1377":"umbes 1377","1350":"1350","1 October 1406":"1. oktoober 1406","1406":"1406","Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southampton, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–1421":"1350–1421","1338–1437":"1338–1437","–Male":"Kuollut","1375–1406":"1375–1406","1377–Male":"1377–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1338":"1338","1377":"1377","1421":"1421","1375":"1375","ABT 1377":"noin 1377","1350":"1350","1 October 1406":"1. lokakuuta 1406","1406":"1406","Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradenham, Buckinghamsh